    <section xml:id="improper-integrals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Improper Integrals</title>

        <p>We begin by looking at the following two examples: We would like to determine the area 
        <ul>
            <li>of the region under the graph of <m>x\mapsto \frac1{x^2}</m> for <m>x\ge 1</m>, and</li>
            <li>of the region under the graph of <m>x\mapsto \frac1{\sqrt{x}}</m> for <m>0\lt x\le 1</m>.</li>
        </ul></p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-improper-integral-1onxsquared">

            <image width="70%" xml:id="improper-integral-1onxsquared">
                <sageplot>
                    p=plot(1/x^2,(x,0,5),ymax=5,aspect_ratio=1)+plot(1/x^2,(x,1,5),fill=True,fillcolor='darkgreen',axes_labels=['$x$','$y$'])
                    p
                </sageplot>
            </image>

            <caption>The improper integral <m>\int_1^{\infty} \frac1{x^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>.</caption>

        </figure>


        <figure xml:id="figure-improper-integral-1onsqrtx">

            <image width="70%" xml:id="improper-integral-1onsqrtx">
                <sageplot>
                    p=plot(1/sqrt(x),(x,0,5),ymax=5,aspect_ratio=1)+plot(1/sqrt(x),(x,0,1),fill=True,fillcolor='darkgreen',axes_labels=['$x$','$y$'])
                    p
                </sageplot>
            </image>

            <caption>The improper integral <m>\int_0^{1} \frac1{\sqrt{x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>.</caption>

        </figure>


        <p>The approach using Riemann sums does not work here: In the first case, partitioning <m>[1,\infty)</m> into finitely many subintervals always gives at least one subinterval with infinite width; in the second case, the height of the first rectangle becomes infinite.</p>

        <p>However, for <m>r\gt 0</m> we have
            <me>\int_1^r\frac1{x^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \left.-\frac1{x}\right|_1^r= 1-\frac1{r},</me> 
        and thus
            <me>\lim_{r\to\infty} \int_1^r\frac1{x^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \lim_{r\to\infty} \left( 1-\frac1{r}\right)=1.</me>
        Since this limit exists (i.e., converges to a finite value),  it is reasonable to set
            <me>\int_1^{\infty}\frac1{x^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x} =  \lim_{r\to\infty} \int_1^r\frac1{x^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = 1.</me>
        </p>

        <p>Similarly, for <m>\varepsilon\gt 0</m> we have
            <me>\int_{\varepsilon}^1\frac1{\sqrt{x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \left. 2\sqrt{x}\right|_{\varepsilon}^1=2-2\sqrt{\varepsilon},</me>
        and thus
            <me>\lim_{\varepsilon\to 0^+}\int_{\varepsilon}^1\frac1{\sqrt{x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \lim_{\varepsilon\to 0^+}2-2\sqrt{\varepsilon}=2.</me>
        Again, since this limit exists, we set
            <me>\int_{0}^1\frac1{\sqrt{x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} =  \lim_{\varepsilon\to 0^+} \int_{\varepsilon}^1\frac1{\sqrt{x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = 2.</me>
        </p>

        <p>So, in both situations we suceed in calculating the area, although the usual approach using Riemann sums does not work. Such integrals are called improper integrals.</p>

        <p>However, this does not always work.</p> 
        <ul>
            <li><p> Neither does <m>\int_1^\infty \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> exist: Since
                <me>\int_1^r\frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \left.\ln|{x}|\right|_1^r=\ln(r)</me>
            for <m>r\gt 0</m>, and thus <m>\ln(r)\to\infty</m> as <m>r\to\infty</m>, the integral <m>\int_1^\infty \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> does not converge. We also say that the integral <m>\int_1^\infty \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> diverges (to infinity) or that <m>\frac1{x}</m> is not integrable over <m>[1,\infty)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Nor does <m>\int_0^1 \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> exist: Since
                <me>\int_{\varepsilon}^1\frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \left.\ln|{x}|\right|_{\varepsilon}^1=-\ln(\varepsilon)=\ln(1/\varepsilon)</me>
            for <m>\varepsilon\gt 0</m>, and thus <m>\ln(1/\varepsilon)\to\infty</m> as <m>\varepsilon\to 0^+</m>, the integral <m>\int_0^1 \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> does not converge. We also say that the integral <m>\int_0^1 \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> diverges (to infinity) or that <m>\frac1{x}</m> is not integrable over <m>(0,1]</m>.</p></li>
        </ul>

        <p>An integral can also be improper if the integrand is not defined at an interior point of the interval we are integrating over. E.g., the integral
            <me>\int_{-1}^1\frac1{\sqrt{|{x}|}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</me>
        is improper, and we calculate
        <md>
            <mrow>\int_{-1}^1\frac1{\sqrt{|{x}|}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} =\int_{-1}^0\frac1{\sqrt{|{x}|}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}+\int_{0}^1\frac1{\sqrt{|{x}|}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} </mrow> 
            <mrow>=\lim_{\tilde{\varepsilon}\to 0^-} \int_{-1}^{\tilde{\varepsilon}}\frac1{\sqrt{|{x}|}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}+\lim_{\varepsilon\to 0^+} \int_{\varepsilon}^1\frac1{\sqrt{|{x}|}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} =\lim_{\tilde{\varepsilon}\to 0^-} \int_{-1}^{\tilde{\varepsilon}}\frac1{\sqrt{-x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}+\lim_{\varepsilon\to 0^+} \int_{\varepsilon}^1\frac1{\sqrt{x}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} </mrow>
            <mrow> = \lim_{\tilde{\varepsilon}\to 0^-} \left.-2\sqrt{-x}\right|_{-1}^{\tilde{\varepsilon}} + \lim_{\varepsilon\to 0^+} \left.2\sqrt{x}\right|_{\varepsilon}^1=(-0+2)+(2-0)=4. </mrow>
        </md></p>

        <example xml:id="example-improper-integral">
            <title>Diverging cross-section and finite volume</title>
            <p>As we have seen above, the area enclosed by the graph of <m>x\mapsto\frac1{x}</m> for <m>x\ge 1</m> diverges to infinity. However, the solid of revolution that we obtain by rotating this area around the <m>x</m>-axis has finite volume: In general, rotating the area under <m>x\mapsto f(x)</m> over the interval <m>[a,b]</m> around the <m>x</m>-axis, yields a solid of revolution with volume <m>\pi\int_a^b (f(x))^2\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>. So, in the case <m>f(x)=\frac1{x}</m> for <m>x\ge 1</m>, we get the volume
                <me>\pi \int_1^{\infty} \frac1{x^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x} = \pi\cdot 1 = \pi.</me>
            </p> 

            <figure xml:id="figure-improper-integral-oneonx">

                <image width="70%" xml:id="improper-integral-oneonx">
                    <sageplot>
                        p=plot(1/x,(x,0,5),ymax=5,aspect_ratio=1)+plot(1/x,(x,1,5),fill=True,fillcolor='darkgreen',axes_labels=['$x$','$y$'])
                        p
                    </sageplot>
                </image>

                <caption>The diverging (improper) integral <m>\int_1^{\infty} \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>.</caption>

            </figure>

            <figure xml:id="figure-improper-integral-1onx-revolution">

                <image width="100%" xml:id="improper-integral-1onx-revolution">
                    <sageplot>
                        from sage.manifolds.utilities import set_axes_labels
                        x,y=var('x,y')
                        p=parametric_plot3d([x,cos(y)/x,sin(y)/x],(x,1,4.8),(y,0,2*pi),color='darkgreen')+point((.2,-1.8,-1.8),opacity=0)+point((.2,2,2),opacity=0)
                        pa = set_axes_labels(p, 'x', 'y', 'z', color='red')
                        pa
                    </sageplot>
                </image>

                <caption>The solid of revolution corresponding to <m>\int_1^{\infty} \frac1{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>. This solid of revolution with diverging cross section has finite volume.</caption>

            </figure>


        </example>

        <exercise  xml:id="exercise-improper-integrals">
            <p>Evaluate the integral <m>\int_{-1}^2\frac{y}{\sqrt{y+1}}\operatorname{d}\!{y}</m>.</p>
        </exercise>

    </section>


    <section xml:id="integration-using-partial-fractions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Special Integration Techniques: Partial Fractions</title>

        <p>Integrals of rational functions can explicitly be calculated. More precisely, if <m>p, q</m> are polynomials (with real coefficients) and <m>q(x)\neq 0</m> for all <m>x\in[a,b]</m>, then we can evaluate the integral
            <me>\int_a^b \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</me>
        once we know the roots of <m>q(x)</m> (i.e., for which <m>x</m> the polynomial <m>q(x)</m> becomes zero), since this enables us to find an antiderivative of the continuous function <m>\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m>.</p>

        <p>We first note that if the degree of <m>p</m> is greater than or equal to the degree of <m>q</m>, polynomial division yields
            <me> \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} = f(x)+\frac{r(x)}{q(x)},</me>
        where <m>f</m> and <m>r</m> are polynomials, and the degree of <m>r</m> is strictly less than the degree of <m>q</m>. Note that the polynomial <m>f</m> can be easily integrated. </p>

        <p>We now simplify the rational function <m>\frac{r(x)}{q(x)}</m> using partial fractions. This is based on the following facts:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><p>Every polynomial <m>q(x)</m> with real coefficients is the product of a constant, linear polynomials of the form <m>x-c</m> with <m>c\in \mathbb{R}</m>, and quadratic polynomials of the form <m>x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d}</m> with <m>d,\tilde{d}\in\mathbb{R}</m> and <m>d^2 - 4\tilde{d} \lt 0</m> (which is the same thing as saying that the polynomial <m>x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d}</m> has no real roots, but a pair <m>z,\overline{z}</m> of complex conjugate roots).</p>

            <p>This result is a consequence of the so-called <em>Fundamental Theorem of Algebra</em>. see Theorem <xref ref="theorem-FTA" />.</p></li>
            <li><p>We can thus write the denominator <m>q(x)</m> as the product
            <md>
                <mrow>q(x) = &amp; C\cdot (x-c_1)^{k_1}\cdot  (x-c_2)^{k_2}\cdots (x-c_n)^{k_n}\cdot</mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; (x^2 + d_1\,x + \tilde{d}_1)^{\ell_1}\cdot  (x^2 + d_2\,x + \tilde{d}_2)^{\ell_2}\cdots (x^2 + d_m\,x + \tilde{d}_m)^{\ell_m} </mrow>
            </md>
            where <m>c_i, d_i, \tilde{d}_i, C\in\mathbb{R}</m>, <m>k_i, \ell_i\in\mathbb{N}</m> and <m>n,m\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}</m> (where <m>n=0</m> means that there is no linear factors, and <m>m=0</m> that there is no quadratic factor).</p></li>
            <li><p>Assuming that <m>C=1</m> (in other words, that the coefficient of the highest power of <m>q(x)</m> is <m>1</m>) and that <m>r(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> have no common factor, we can express <m>\frac{r(x)}{q(x)}</m> using partial fractions. To this end, any factor <m>(x-c)^{k}</m> of <m>q(x)</m> contributes
                <me>\frac{A_1}{x-c}+\frac{A_2}{(x-c)^2}+\ldots+\frac{A_k}{(x-c)^k},</me>
            and any factor <m>(x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d})^{\ell}</m> contributes
                <me> \frac{B_1x+D_1}{x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d}}+\frac{B_2x+D_2}{(x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d})^2}+\ldots+\frac{B_{\ell}x+D_{\ell}}{(x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d})^{\ell}} </me>
            where <m>A_i, B_i, D_i\in\mathbb{R}</m> are (uniquely determined) constants.</p></li>
            <li><p>Therefore, expressing <m>\frac{r(x)}{q(x)}</m> using partial fractions leads to a sum of expressions that can be individually integrated.</p></li>
        </ul>

        <p>We look at two examples.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-integration-using-partial-fractions-1">
            <title>Using partial fractions: Only linear terms</title>
            <p>We want to find an antiderivative of <m>\frac{5x^2+12 x+47}{(x-3)(x+5)^2}</m>. Using partial fractions, we have to find real constants <m>A, B_1</m> and <m>B_2</m> such that
                <me>\frac{5x^2+12 x+47}{(x-3)(x+5)^2} = \frac{A}{x-3}+\frac{B_1}{x+5}+\frac{B_2}{(x+5)^2}.</me>
            To this end, we multiply this equation with the denominator <m>q(x)=(x-3)(x+5)^2</m> to obtain
            <md>
                <mrow> 5x^2+12x+47 &amp; = A\, (x+5)^2+B_1\,(x-3)(x+5)+B_2\,(x+3) </mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; = (A+B_1)\, x^2+(10\,A+2\,B_1+B_3)\,x</mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; \qquad +(25\,A-15\,B_1-3\,B_2).</mrow>
            </md>
            Either by comparing coefficients or by using appropriate values for <m>x</m>, this yields
                <me>A=2,\quad B_1=3,\quad\text{and}\quad B_2=-14.</me>
            Thus, we have
                <me>\frac{5x^2+12 x+47}{(x-3)(x+5)^2} = \frac{2}{x-3}+\frac{3}{x+5}+\frac{-14}{(x+5)^2},</me>
            and we therefore find 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\int\frac{5x^2+12 x+47}{(x-3)(x+5)^2}\operatorname{d}\!{x} &amp; =2\,\ln|{x-3}| +3\,\ln|{x+5}| + \frac{14}{x+5}+C</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; =\ln\left(({x-3})^2\cdot|{x+5}|^3\right) + \frac{14}{x+5}+C.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-integration-using-partial-fractions-2">
            <title>Using partial fractions: Including a quadratic term</title>
            <p>We want to find an antiderivative of <m>\frac{3x^2+4x+29}{(x-1)(x^2+4x+13)}</m>. Since <m>x^2+4x+13=(x+2)^2+9</m>, the second factor in the denominator has no real roots. Using partial fractions, we here have to find real constants <m>A, B</m> and <m>D</m> such that
                <me>\frac{3x^2+4x+29}{(x-1)(x^2+4x+13)} = \frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{Bx+D}{x^2+4x+13}.</me>
            To this end, we multply this equation with the denominator <m>q(x)=(x-1)(x^2+4x+13)</m> to obtain
            <md>
                <mrow>3x^2+4x+29 &amp; = A\, (x^2+4x+13)+(Bx+D)(x-1) </mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; = (A+B)\, x^2+(4\,A-B+D)\,x+(13\,A-D) </mrow>
            </md>
            Either by comparing coefficients or by using appropriate values for <m>x</m>, this yields
                <me>A=2,\quad B=1,\quad\text{and}\quad D=-3.</me>
            Thus, we have
            <md>
                <mrow>\frac{3x^2+4x+29}{(x-1)(x^2+4x+13)} &amp; = \frac{2}{x-1}+\frac{x-3}{x^2+4x+13}</mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; = \frac{2}{x-1}+\frac{\frac12(2x+4)-5}{x^2+4x+13}</mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; = \frac{2}{x-1}+\frac12\cdot \frac{2x+4}{x^2+4x+13}+\frac{-5}{x^2+4x+13}</mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; = \frac{2}{x-1}+\frac12\cdot \frac{2x+4}{x^2+4x+13}-\frac{5}{(x+2)^2+9}</mrow>
                <mrow> &amp; = \frac{2}{x-1}+\frac12\cdot \frac{2x+4}{x^2+4x+13}-\frac{5}{9}\cdot \frac1{\left(\frac{x+2}3\right)^2+1},</mrow>
            </md>
            and we therefore find
            <md>
                <mrow>\int \frac{3x^2+4x+29}{(x-1)(x^2+4x+13)}\operatorname{d}\!{x} </mrow>
                <mrow> = 2\,\ln|{x-1}|+\frac12\,\ln|{x^2+4x+13}|-\frac59\cdot 3\,\arctan\left(\frac{x+2}3\right)+C </mrow>
                <mrow> = 2\,\ln|{x-1}|+\frac12\,\ln|{x^2+4x+13}|-\frac53\, \arctan\left(\frac{x+2}3\right)+C</mrow>
                <mrow> = \ln\left((x-1)^2\cdot\sqrt{x^2+4x+13}\right)-\frac53\, \arctan\left(\frac{x+2}3\right)+C.</mrow>
            </md></p>
        </example>

        <p>The only difficulty left now, are integrals with an 
            integrand of the form 
            <m>\frac{Bx+D}{(x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d})^{k}}</m>. 
            To this end, we note that 
            <m>\frac{x+d}{(x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d})^{k}}</m> 
            is easy to integrate, so really all that is left are 
            integrands of the form 
            <m>\frac{1}{(x^2 + d\,x + \tilde{d})^{k}}</m>, or 
            actually (after completing the square etc., compare 
            <xref ref="example-integration-using-partial-fractions-2"/>) 
            integrands of the form <m>\frac{1}{(x^2+1)^{k}}</m>. 
            In order to evaluate the latter, one use a (recursive) reduction 
            formula that is discussed in 
            <xref ref="exercise-integration-partial-fractions-reduction-1"/>.
        </p>


        <exercise xml:id="exercise-integration-partial-fractions-1">
