     <section xml:id="integration-using-trig-substitution" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Special Integration Techniques: Trigonometric Substitutions (or the demise thereof)</title>

        <p>There are four types of integrals that we can effectively compute using trigonometric substitutions. They are
        <ul>
            <li><m>\int x^n R^k\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>,</li>
            <li><m>\int \frac{x^n}{R^k}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>,</li>
            <li><m>\int \frac{R^k}{x^n}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>, and </li>
            <li><m>\int \frac1{x^n R^k}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>,</li>
        </ul>
        where <m>n\ge 0</m>, <m>k\gt 0</m> are integers, <m>k</m> is odd, and <m>R</m> has one of the following three forms
        <ul>
            <li><m>R = \sqrt{a^2-x^2}</m>; in this case the domain of integration is contained in <m>[-a,a]</m>,</li>
            <li><m>R = \sqrt{a^2+x^2}</m>; in this case the domain of integration is contained in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>,</li>
            <li><m>R = \sqrt{x^2-a^2}</m>; in this case the domain of integration is contained either in <m>(-\infty,-a]</m> or <m>[a,+\infty)</m>,</li>
        </ul>
        where <m>a\in\mathbb{R}</m> is some constant.
        </p>

        <p>Note that if <m>k</m> is even, we are in the situation of the last section, i.e., we have a rational function.</p>

        <remark>
            <title>Approach using trigonometric functions</title>
            <p>For trigonometric substitutions, the form of the term <m>R</m> determines which substitution to use. If the integral involves<fn>Hyperbolic trigonometric functions can also be used, for <m>R = \sqrt{a^2+x^2}</m> substitute <m>x=a\sinh(t)</m> (note that <m>\frac{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}{\operatorname{d}\!{t}}=a\cos(t)</m>) and use the identity <m>1+\sinh^2(t)=\cosh^2(t)</m>.</fn>
            <ul>
                <li><m>R = \sqrt{a^2-x^2}</m> then substitute <m>x=a\sin(t)</m> (note that <m>\frac{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}{\operatorname{d}\!{t}}=a\cos(t)</m>) and use the identity <m>1-\sin^2(t)=\cos^2(t)</m>;</li>
                <li><m>R = \sqrt{a^2+x^2}</m> then substitute <m>x=a\tan(t)=a\frac{\sin(t)}{\cos(t)}</m> (note that <m>\frac{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}{\operatorname{d}\!{t}}=a(1+\tan^2(t))=a/\cos^2(t)</m>) and use the<fn>Yes, we avoid mentioning the secant function here and do not write <m>1+\tan^2(t)=\sec^2(t)</m>. If calculus textbooks use the secant and cosecant function excessively, alarm bells should ring <mdash /> probably, there is cleaner alternative way!</fn> identity <m>1+\tan^2(t)=\frac1{\cos^2(t)}</m>;</li>
                <li><m>R = \sqrt{x^2-a^2}</m> then substitute <m>x=a/\cos(t)</m> (note that <m>\frac{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}{\operatorname{d}\!{t}}=a\tan(t)/\cos(t)=a\sin(t)/\cos^2(t)</m>) and use the identity <m>\frac1{\cos^2(t)}-1=\tan^2(t)</m>.</li>
            </ul>
            The outcome in each case is a function in <m>\cos(t)</m> and <m>\sin(t)</m>, and we got rid of the square root expression. So, let us now explore how we can integrate functions in <m>\cos(t)</m> and <m>\sin(t)</m>.</p>
        </remark>

        <note>
            <title>Integrating functions with sine and cosine</title>
            <p>In order to evaluate an integral of the form <m>\int f(\cos(t),\sin(t))\operatorname{d}\!{t}</m>, where <m>f</m> is some function, one can use yet another substitution: If we put <m>u=\tan\left(\frac{t}2\right)</m>, elementary trigonometry yields the simple formulas
                <me>\sin(t) = \frac{2u}{1+u^2}\qquad \cos(t) = \frac{1-u^2}{1+u^2},</me>
            and by differentiation we obtain
                <me>\frac{\operatorname{d}\!{u}}{\operatorname{d}\!{t}}=\frac1{2\cos^2(t/2)}=\frac{1+u^2}2.</me>
            What is the result on the integrals we consider in this section? After the two substitutions we now arrived at an integral of the form <m>\int \frac{p(u)}{q(u)}\operatorname{d}\!{u}</m> where <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are polynomials in <m>u</m>, i.e., the integrand is now a rational function in <m>u</m>. Using partial fractions, see the previous section (Section <xref ref="integration-using-partial-fractions" />), we can now evaluate this integral.</p>
        </note>

        <p>This two-stage process should leave you wondering if we really need the trigonometric substitutions. After all, their only purpose, in some sense, is only to get rid of the quare root term before another substitution brings us back to <xref ref="integration-using-partial-fractions" />.</p>

        <p>In fact, the integrals of the four forms <m>\int x^n R^k\operatorname{d}\!{x}, \ldots, \int \frac1{x^n R^k}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> can be computed using one of two<fn>Recall that we needed a different trigonometric substitution for each of the three forms of <m>R</m>.</fn> substitutions; namely, we let 
            <me>u^2 = R^2 \quad\text{for}\ n\ \text{odd}</me>
        and
            <me>u^2 = \frac{R^2}{x^2} \quad\text{for}\ n\ \text{even}.</me>
        Notice that the form of <m>R</m> does not play a role here, only the power <m>n</m> of the polynomial term.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-trig-substitution-demise-odd-1">
            <title>Integrand with odd <m>n</m></title>

            <p>Let us evaluate <m>\int\frac{x^3}{(9-x^2)^{5/2}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>. This is an integral of the form  <m>\int \frac{x^n}{R^k}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> where <m>R=\sqrt{9-x^2}=\sqrt{3^2-x^2}</m>, <m>k=5</m> and <m>n=3</m>. Since <m>n</m> is odd, we choose the substitution <m>u^2=9-x^2</m> which by implicit differentiation yields <m>2u \frac{\operatorname{d}\!{u}}{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}=-2x</m> and thus <m>\operatorname{d}\!{x} = -\frac{u}{x}\operatorname{d}\!{u}</m>. We therefore obtain
                <md>
                    <mrow>\int\frac{x^3}{(9-x^2)^{5/2}}\operatorname{d}\!{x} &amp; = \int\frac{x^3}{u^{5}}\,\left(-\frac{u}{x}\right)\operatorname{d}\!{u}</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\int\frac{x^2}{u^{4}}\operatorname{d}\!{u}</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\int\frac{9-u^2}{u^{4}}\operatorname{d}\!{u}</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\int\left(\frac9{u^4}-\frac1{u^2}\right)\operatorname{d}\!{u}</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\left(-\frac13\cdot\frac9{u^3}+\frac1{u}\right)+C</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = \frac3{u^3}-\frac1{u}+C</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = \frac3{(\sqrt{9-x^2})^3}-\frac1{\sqrt{9-x^2}}+C.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-trig-substitution-demise-even-1">
            <title>Integrand with even <m>n</m></title>

            <p>Let us evaluate <m>\int\frac{\sqrt{16+x^2}}{x^4}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m>. This is an integral of the form  <m>\int \frac{R^k}{x^n}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> where <m>R=\sqrt{16+x^2}=\sqrt{4^2+x^2}</m>, <m>k=1</m> and <m>n=4</m>. Since <m>n</m> is even, we choose the substitution <m>u^2=\frac{16+x^2}{x^2}=\frac{16}{x^2}+1</m> which by implicit differentiation yields <m>2u \frac{\operatorname{d}\!{u}}{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}=-\frac{32}{x^3}</m> and thus <m>\operatorname{d}\!{x} = -\frac{x^3u}{16}\operatorname{d}\!{u}</m>. Noting that <m>x^2 u^2=R^2=16+x^2</m>, and thus <m>\sqrt{16+x^2}=x\,u</m>, we obtain
                <md>
                    <mrow>\int\frac{\sqrt{16+x^2}}{x^4}\operatorname{d}\!{x} &amp; = \int\frac{x\,u}{x^{4}}\,\left(-\frac{x^3 u}{16}\right)\operatorname{d}\!{u}</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\frac1{16}\int {u^{2}} \operatorname{d}\!{u}</mrow>>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\frac1{48} u^3+C</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = -\frac1{48} \frac{(\sqrt{16+x^2})^3}{x^3}+C.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </example>


        <p>Notice that the resulting integrands in <m>u</m> are, as expected, again rational functions. As a consequence, compare the previous <xref ref="integration-using-partial-fractions" />, the resulting integrals in <m>u</m> involve only linear combinations of integral power functions, the functions <m>\ln|1+u|</m>, <m>\ln|1-u|</m>, and the inverse tangent function <m>\arctan(u)</m>. In particular, we do not need the inverse sine or the inverse secant functions<fn>In fact, one has <m>\arcsin(x)=\arctan\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\right)</m> (where <m>|x|\le 1</m>) and <m>\operatorname{arcsec}(x)=\arccos\left(\frac1{x}\right) = \frac{\pi}2-\arctan\left(\frac{\operatorname{sgn}(x)}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}\right)</m> (where <m>|x|\gt 1</m> and <m>\operatorname{sgn}(x)</m> denotes the sign of <m>x</m>). One may obtain these identities, e.g., by noting that <m>\frac{\operatorname{d}}{\operatorname{d}\!{x}}{\arcsin(x)}=\frac1{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</m>, which is obtained by the <em>inverse function theorem</em>, and calculating the anti-derivative of <m>\frac1{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</m> alternatively using the substitution discussed in this section. 
        There are similar formulas for <m>\arccos</m> and <m>\operatorname{arccosec}</m> as well as further formulas like <m>\arcsin(x) = 2\arctan\left(\frac{x}{1+\sqrt{1-x^2}}\right)</m> and <m>\arccos(x)=2\arctan\left(\frac{\sqrt{1-x}}{\sqrt{1+x}}\right)</m>. Note that the inverse tangent is therefore the only inverse trigonometric function really needed (well, one also only needs one trigonometric function to calculate the values of any other one, so this is should not come as a surprise), and the inverse tangent function appears here through the partial fraction expansion, see Section <xref ref="integration-using-partial-fractions" />.</fn> to compute integrals of the types considered in this section.</p>

        <exercise>
            <p>Find the following integrals:
            <ol marker="a.)">
                <li><m>\int\frac{\sqrt{x^2-25}}{x}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> where <m>x\gt 5</m>;</li>
                <li><m>\int x^2{\sqrt{1+x^2}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m></li>
                <li><m>\int\frac{x^2}{\sqrt{16x^2-25}}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> where <m>x\gt \frac54</m>;</li>
                <li><m>\int {(\sqrt{4x^2-5})^3}\operatorname{d}\!{x}</m> where <m>x\gt \sqrt{5}/2</m>.</li>
            </ol></p>
        </exercise>


    </section>

